# Store Scheduling Optimization (SSO)
**TELUS · Senior AI Product Manager · 2024 – Present**

---

## The problem

TELUS retail stores were being staffed on intuition and static schedules that did not account for actual customer demand patterns. When stores hit above 80% occupancy without enough staff, sales conversion dropped significantly — customers waited, got frustrated, or left. Analysis proved this was costing TELUS over $1M annually in lost conversions at peak times, with a three-year recovery opportunity of $15M.

The existing process: Excel-based scheduling planned 40–50 days in advance, using historical rules of thumb. No real-time signal. No predictive capability. No way to account for seasonality, local events, or promotional periods.

---

## My role

End-to-end AI Product Manager for the SSO initiative. I owned problem framing, technical architecture decisions, phased rollout strategy, data access resolution, stakeholder alignment, and governance.

---

## The product I defined

A two-stage AI intelligence engine replacing Excel-based scheduling across 252 TELUS retail stores.

### Stage 1: Traffic Forecasting Model
A time-series predictive engine that forecasts customer footfall at the store level, learning from:
- Historical traffic patterns
- Seasonality (holidays, promotional periods, TELUS-specific campaign dates)
- Store tier and transaction-type mix (mobility vs. home internet vs. other)

### Stage 2: Labor Optimizer
A regression model that translates traffic forecasts into specific required staffing hours, factoring in:
- Store tier and size
- Sales trend trajectories
- Transaction-type complexity

### The "Constraint Layer" (my design)
A post-processing business logic engine I specifically designed to apply budget caps and "saleable vs. non-saleable" rules to every AI recommendation before it reaches a store manager. This ensured all AI outputs remained operationally feasible — a responsible AI design principle that also drove adoption, because store managers trusted outputs that respected their operational reality.

---

## Critical strategic decisions I made

**The 80% efficiency threshold as the North Star metric:** I identified that the product's core value proposition was maintaining occupancy between 60–75% — not just predicting traffic. By setting the model's target output in terms of occupancy rather than pure accuracy, I tied AI performance directly to the business outcome we were optimizing for. This was the decision that made the $15M revenue recovery claim credible.

**Phased MVP — 23 stores first:** Rather than attempting a full 252-store rollout, I scoped the initial pilot to 23 stores in Alberta and Quebec, deliberately chosen to represent different utilization rates. The pilot validated the model's scalability before full commitment. This was the right call — it also gave us real-world data to improve the constraint layer before broader rollout.

**Challenging the "40–50 day planning window" assumption:** The legacy requirement assumed you needed to plan staffing 40–50 days in advance. I pushed the team to test predictions at 1-week and 2-week intervals and proved to stakeholders that shorter forecast windows significantly improved accuracy. This insight challenged an organizational assumption that had never been tested quantitatively.

**Dual interface strategy — Looker and Tableau:** I recognized that the planning team needed deep-dive budget analysis (Looker) while store managers needed simple daily scheduling recommendations (Tableau). Building one interface for both audiences would have served neither well. I defined both, and adoption reflected that decision.

