## Fires I put out

**The 2025 funding gap:** Capital funding for the project was zeroed out in 2025. Rather than letting the project die, I maintained stakeholder engagement through ongoing follow-ups, scope preservation, and re-prioritization conversations. When 2026 funding opened, SSO was at the top of the list. Projects that go quiet during a funding gap rarely come back.

**Data access block:** The project faced a critical delay from a lack of raw traffic data access. I escalated to leadership, coordinated directly with data platform owners to bypass distribution list issues, and secured access to the Data Hub within the same week. A week-long delay is survivable. A month-long delay with no owner pushing it is not.

**Stakeholder redundancy resolution:** A separate retail planning team (Partap Tiwana) had simultaneously requested the same AI scheduling capability. Rather than allowing two parallel efforts to fragment engineering resources, I identified the duplication, merged their requirements into the existing SSO roadmap, and prevented fragmented development. One product, one roadmap, shared benefit.

